explanation:
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: need the function prototype and/or implementation to determine whether it writes through the OS_object_token_t * parameter (fills/modifies the token) or only reads it. If it only reads the pointed object the parameter should be const; if it writes the pointer must be non-const.
- OS_CondVarUnlock_Impl: need its prototype/implementation to see whether it mutates the token passed (&token). Its signature (const or non-const pointer) and body determine whether the address-of-local should be to a const-qualified type.
- OS_object_token_t: the typedef/struct definition is required to know the pointed-to type (is it a struct, contains mutable members, etc.) and whether any internal members are modified by callees — relevant to deciding const qualification.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: OS_CondVarUnlock_Impl calls this (per call graph); its prototype/implementation may show whether the token is passed as const or is modified downstream — needed to trace whether token is ever mutated.
- osal_id_t: the typedef of the id type (used as var_id) is needed for complete type context of OS_ObjectIdGetById prototype; while not directly about token constness, it ensures accurate prototype matching during analysis.
- int32: typedef/definition of int32 (return type) to ensure correct interpretation of return values (e.g. OS_SUCCESS) when assessing control flow that leads to pointer passing.

Provide the prototypes/implementations for these symbols so the analyzer can determine whether any pointer parameter could safely be const-qualified without changing behavior.
